Right-wing populists triumph in Austria, they have 29 percent in total
Preliminary results show that the early parliamentary elections in Austria resulted in a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current Grand Coalition, as well as a notable strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party, where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly large losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria, the governor of Carinthia, Jirg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at the national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SP) remain, with 29.8 percent of the vote, the leading political force in the country, however, compared with the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The OVP, who with 25.6 percent lost nearly nine percent of the vote, ended up even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major post-war parties; especially for the popular party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Still in early July, when the PVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SP.
Voters obviously punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations were made about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary council of the leadership of the party.
Such a move would a priori facilitate the path to the outcome of the election result, which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the SP and VP grand coalition.
Nevertheless, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free (FP) would have obtained 18 percent and BZ - 11 percent of the votes - the Socialists expressed at the same time the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FP was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZ - separated from the European Union) on a common government, which was part of the sanctions.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently relies on this development.
The last party to have access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell from third to fifth among the Austrian political parties.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four percent limit and entered parliament.
