A Czech referee the fight for the seabed
It is approaching a wall-mounted electronic map, on which is represented Australia and adjacent marine areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
This area is however as large as the continent itself,” says Italian jurist Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the team of thirty members of the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
Its head, the director of the division, the Czech jurist Vaclav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
The ardour at work and the enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a world little known until now, rich in natural resources.
Oil, minerals and other mineral resources can be found there, but also unknown living organisms, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A background larger than the land
Coastal states have now begun to aspire vehemently to the new submarine territories.
According to a UN convention, they use their rights, which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter can, according to the convention, claim exclusively to all the resources of the continental shelf.
"To simplify, is considered continental shelf the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the limits of the littoral sea, often also beyond the 200 nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone,” says Mikulka.
The request of the country in question to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf must be supported by a large scientific-technical documentation, based on many expensive prospecting and meticulousness.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the commission has dealt with five requests, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful,” Mikulka added.
The success of Australia, which is the first to have significantly expanded its underwater possessions, has recently had a worldwide impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which the commission attributed to it last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometres, which is the country's six-fold increase.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in exploration.
The benefit they will derive in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they project themselves, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their applications.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no state enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
“Nevertheless, make no mistake, the seabed is not a Klondike,” said director Mikulka, adding that “its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract.”
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern bloc within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, under the terms of the Convention, it was granted, along with investors from a few other States, the status of a so-called "pioneer investor".
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area surveyed by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is hectic, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract on an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese,” enumerates Ind Pakshi Rajan, another jurist.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, provides an example of such a concretion.
It recalls a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoem, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
