Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey thought of joining the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate its hinterland.
On the east side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps from Asia, is one of the finest relics of his fallen imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha station was designed in a neo-Renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that’s what the guides tell us.
The monument is located on horseback at the bottom of the platforms, equipped with observation towers at each of its angles, like some German provincial town halls.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is in ruins.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, we no longer have any doubt about the size of the company, which represents a passage to the west.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German association, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, backward in the game of imperialism, wanted to achieve its medieval ambitions of domination thanks to this railway that arrives in Damascus, Baghdad as well as the land better known as Saudi Arabia.
But German imperialist ambitions collapsed during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation of its surrounding area, brought about by the icy borders of the Cold War, is over.
The British and Empire forces advanced against Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof.
Turkish sources say this is sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly fallen into ruin, engulfed in the meanders of history.
But today, the rail crossing to Anatolia and all the eastern points, at least symbolically, serves to highlight Turkey’s expanding diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of its surrounding area, brought about by the icy borders of the Cold War
Now is the time for a new commitment policy.
The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To judge the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded a sleeper car in the direction of the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit Turkish MP AKP Suat Kiniklioglu, one of the foreign policy experts.
The next morning, after a journey of 10 and a half hours, shaken on noisy rails whose cadence recalled the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived, in the Turkish capital – presented as a new city of a new secular state, turning its back on its German past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents an example of a change in the Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi accompanied me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern structure, expressly built of stone and steel, in a developing neighborhood, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and by many pastries in which middle managers in suit-tie-men and women- meet for morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
Costume, tie and he even has a Black Berry.
“The aim of this foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its back country.
Now she has to look east and west at the same time.
This was not the case for both of them.
She had to do both.
"But then, at some point, I asked if 'shouldn't Turkey choose?'"
“Turkey,” he said, “doesn’t want to have to choose between the two.”
He then pointed out an aspect that almost everyone I spoke to recited to me by heart: The Turkish railway goes not only to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus, and around the Black Sea, so it is as much an advantage for Europe and the United States as for Turkey itself.
With the integration of Turkey, the message seems to draw a Europe traveling metaphorically on the rails to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpasha station, after another night without sleep, I thought of these two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who followed the construction of this building 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to see that the European ambitions of the Middle East could, in large part, be in the hands of Turkey.
While I was waiting at the terminal, the ferry to cross the Bosphorus, I remembered the period when Turkey had been called "the sick man of Europe".
At least, there is no longer any doubt on the continent that could claim this fascinating country.
Memoirs of Vernon Handley, and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: Musical director at Guildford since 1962, Vermon "Tod" Handley (died September 11) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
Already part of his musical project for the city, he founded the fantastic youth choir Proteus the following year.
The choir was supposed to include the under-21s, but before Proteus could sing his last song in 1979, many of us who were over 20 refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (which changed form according to mythology) represented the will and ability of the choir to handle any type of music was presented to it, whether madrigal or Messianic.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often impressive, always exciting, thanks to the inspiration of a single man, and his enthusiasm for music, which remained constant over the years.
Remember how Tod used to tell us to “let the music speak for itself.”
He would have said, "The composer knows what he wants."
It’s all there, in the music.
So sing!"
His wand technique was absolutely clear, precise, even if never dictatorial or appearing.
Whatever the musical standard, he raised it much higher.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If a driver were to be named a knight, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the decades from 1962 to 1982, when he was driving the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the past 40 years, I’ve seen over a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that none of them have ever disappointed me – and, sometimes, they even inspired me.
Tod Handley held such a rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He hated drivers who, according to him, “only focus on certain people.”
He will be missed by many of us.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (died 25 September) states that "in 1946 he had resumed his studies in economic history, at Oxford, and in 1950 became a member of Houblon-Norma research, while he was doing a BSc, an MA and a PhD".
This is from the letter of the author of Woodruff in Beyond Nab End, but it is not correct.
From 1946 to 1953 he was Professor of Economic History at the University of Nottingham, and at the same time completed a PhD thesis on the British plastics industry, under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers; it was subsequently published in 1958 under the title The British Rubber Industry.
In the 1950s and 51s in the United States, he studied at Hoblon Norman, and in the summer of 1952, at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for Illinois.
The reason Woodruff chose to hide this part of his past remains unknown.
