The ‘bee car’ that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired, this time, by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center made this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan Safety Shield.
This robot will allow the brand’s vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But most important are the bee’s compound eyes, capable of seeing in an angle of over 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly continuously inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers developed what is called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles that are within a distance of two meters and a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by bifurcating its wheels by 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Displacement Laboratory and principal engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, nor diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a function of rotation, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
"Every second this device must only process information and act on that data.
It doesn’t need to retain the information or intuitive logic of prior maneuvers, which is why it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
It may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes.”
This represents the first car to develop new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced in production cars in a decade or so after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles on the road.
