Morgan Stanley opens its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the first bank in Japan, which will pay $9 billion to take 21% of its capital, a news welcomed by a sharp decline in its share price.
A week after unveiling an interim deal, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9 percent of Morgan Stanley common shares at a unit price of $25.25, or a total amount of $3 billion.
The price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as of August 31.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities with a 10% return and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall deal would be based on an average unit price of $29, or 28 percent above its current price.
Morgan Stanley, however, lost 6.79% at $23.07 around 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to bank holding status,” said John Mack, chief executive of Morgan Stanley.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to diversify its activities but puts it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street’s biggest names to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday further show that the deal has been changed in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG’s executive director, told Tokyo, “we thought the stake would be entirely made up of common shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of earnings per share.
Under the agreement, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into common shares within a year if they trade more than 50% above the conversion price, or around $47, during a given period.
Morgan Stanley says the capital provided by MUFG will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase liquidity.
A spokesperson for the group declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to post a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had “clearly” cut its balance sheet since late August.
The past few weeks have been challenging for the group, which has seen its stock price halve as the cost of insurance against a risk of default on its debt soared.
This cost was falling on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
