Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Rebuilding the Republic around 21st Century Socialism.
This is the joint project of the Venezuelan Hugo Chavez, the Bolivian Evo Morales and the Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, it is the third who put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results of 80% of the vote.
According to these results, the "no" vote received 28%, 7% of the votes were void and 0.7% were white votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half the vote plus one.
On Sunday, two polls taken at the exit of the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a large victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed in the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The “Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the headquarters of Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chavez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place in calm according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was about a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving for it the "development planning" of a country living mainly from oil extraction by foreign companies and currencies sent by its emigrants.
Carried out by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the Head of State, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million people, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US drug operations.
All 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando has launched the assault against the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at around 3:30 p.m. on a special plane at al-Maza military base, adjoining Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, said on the tarmac the Egyptian Minister of Tourism, Zoheir Garanna.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and a Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous agency, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, carried on board two helicopters, launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," said the official, who requested anonymity.
He said that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
“We have to recognize that we have achieved this result through the professionalism and efficiency of our secret service men, special forces,” he said, without elaborating.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were on board, killing in six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
