Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis bank
The Benelux countries help the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries support, to the tune of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, in this case, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the head of competition of the European Commission.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been growing for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In line with the decision made on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (49%) of the bank’s capital in each of the countries.
The bank will, without a doubt, sell part of its holdings, among which, in the first place, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch organization ABN Amro.
In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company's shares fell 12 percent to their lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group’s capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company’s executives, is not realistic.
The company’s management blames the uncertainty from across the Atlantic, in connection with the adoption of the $700 billion US bailout, for the fall in Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new chief executive.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they were not going to lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank’s customer circle and no agency was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information regarding his drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market is spiraling out of control.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information about the prescription of drugs, in any case, to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program has to be in independent hands, otherwise it's like entrusting your chicken coop to a fox" - Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies depend on the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage, on the state of health of the client who presents, and if they believe that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after learning the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies, the data concerning the purchases of drugs of the person in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, which disease the person suffers from and what is his state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, it refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine at the same time a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do to the insurer except paperwork. However, tiny problems can still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used for migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective for depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data, they must ask the patient's permission before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them with data on drug use, so they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time control of use is becoming more and more difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to expand the circle of control of the authorities over companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he developed his program even further, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus and ultimately, the hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, problems.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit, where the focus will be on cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is a great emerging democratic power that should be given a broader voice in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this question yesterday, at this 9th summit held in Marseilles.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would double trade, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be too ambitious a goal.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights, so that air trade can also take off in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's largest trading partner, on the one hand, and New Delhi, the ninth largest trading partner of the EU, on the other.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan had been strongly condemned, as had all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on that subject had been raised.
The completion of the Doha trade round has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate agenda, including that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 percent until 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as on the need for a global market at next year’s climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 percent until 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported convening an international working meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is now traveling to the French capital, where during a bilateral meeting, he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth twenty billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the information of the news agency, the agreement would cover 15 years.
