Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau at 3,000 meters above sea level in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dismissed the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared," he said at a news conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) reported that hours after the wreckage was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was halted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
By the sixth attempt, in 2002, he had become the first man to complete the round-the-world flight on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had traveled around the world by plane and non-stop.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters in height, on the Andes, but with a copilot.
